<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 
<example newNameSpace>
<p><em>Convert <m>20^{\circ}</m> into radians. Express you answer exactly, using <m>\pi</m>, and simplifying if necessary.</em></p>
  
<p><alert><em>Solution.</em></alert></p>
<p>If you recall the one fact that <m>180^{\circ}</m> is the same as <m>\pi</m> radians, you will always remember the unit fraction required for conversion: <m>\frac{\pi}{180}</m>. Multiply by this <term>unit fraction</term><footnote>A unit fraction is a fraction whose value is equal to <m>1</m>. They are often used for conversions between different units.</footnote> to convert any angle from degrees to radians:
  <me>20^{\circ} = 20 \left(\frac{\pi}{180}\right)\;\text{radians}</me></p>
<p>Next, determine the <term>greatest common factor</term><footnote>also called the greatest common divisor</footnote> of <m>20</m> and <m>180</m>, and divide the numerator and denominator by this value to simplify your answer. The greatest common factor is <m>20</m>. We have,
  <me>20 \left(\frac{\pi}{180}\right) = \frac{\pi}{9}\;\text{radians}.</me>
</p>
</example>


<p>
<ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/precalculus/chapter/topic-1-3/">Textbook link: The Radian Measure of an Angle</ref>
</p>

</hint>

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->  
<solution>
<asList>$sol</asList>
</solution>
</problem>




